using silver staining methods, particularly the Grocott-Gomori methenamine silver (GMS) stain. This staining technique highlights the cyst wall of \u003Cem\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii\u003C/em\u003E, revealing characteristic cup-shaped or crescent-shaped structures that appear dark against a lighter background. Silver staining is essential for visualizing this organism in clinical specimens, especially in bronchoalveolar lavage samples from immunocompromised patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other microorganisms are identified using different staining techniques:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECampylobacter species\u003C/strong\u003E are typically identified using Gram stain (appearing as curved Gram-negative rods) or specific culture methods. Giemsa stain can also be used for \u003Cem\u003ECampylobacter\u003C/em\u003E identification. \u003Cem\u003ECampylobacter\u003C/em\u003E species do not require silver staining for identification.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeishmania species\u003C/strong\u003E are best visualized using Giemsa or Wright stains, which highlight the characteristic amastigotes with their nucleus and kinetoplast within macrophages.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryptococcus neoformans\u003C/strong\u003E is typically identified using India ink preparation (to visualize the capsule) or mucicarmine stain (which stains the capsular polysaccharide red). While silver stains can sometimes be used, they are not the primary method.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENocardia species\u003C/strong\u003E are partially acid-fast and are typically identified using modified acid-fast staining techniques or Gram stain, where they appear as branching, beaded, Gram-positive filaments.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESilver staining remains a crucial diagnostic tool for \u003Cem\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii\u003C/em\u003E, particularly in immunocompromised patients with pneumonia where this organism is a common opportunistic pathogen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pneumocystis jirovecii is identified using silver staining methods such as Grocott-Gomori methenamine silver stain.","Silver staining reveals the characteristic cyst wall of Pneumocystis jirovecii, appearing as dark-stained cup-shaped structures.","Other microorganisms like Campylobacter, Leishmania, Cryptococcus, and Nocardia require different staining techniques for identification."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 402."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78940"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20821"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78940"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-31T17:40:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-31T17:41:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13696"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96220"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/